ctations and Visit Satisfaction at Zoos -- tPart 4: Media -- tIntroduction -- t16. Zoos and the Media -- t17. Zoos Victoria: Branding, Marketing and Designing Multi-Location Zoos -- t18. From Winnie-the-Pooh to Madagascar: Fictional Media Images of the Zoo Experience -- t19. Zoos and Tourism in a Changing World -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aZoos are important and popular tourist attractions. Spread around the world, they are typically located in major cities, with visitation levels comparable to other major attractions. Nature-based attractions constructed in artificial settings, they face the challenge of trying to balance potentially conflicting aims of conservation, education and entertainment. The best are continually developing fresh and effective techniques on visitor interpretation and management, the worst highlight the manipulation of animals for human gratification. Taking a global approach, this book examines the problems and paradoxes of zoos as they try to balance their roles as visitor attractions while repositioning themselves as leading conservation agencies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aTourism. 0aWildlife conservation. 0aZoosxSocial aspects. 4aTourism industry. 4aZoos & wildlife parks. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Industries / Hospitality, Travel & Tourism.2bisacsh  aanimal ethics.  aanimal welfare.  aattraction management.  aecotourism.  anature-based attractions .  atourist attractions.  avisitor experience.  avisitor interpretation .  avisitor management.  awildlife conservation.  azoo tourism.1 aBoksberger, Philipp, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCatibog-Sinha, Corazon, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabular